# Living Docs — Auto-Update Rule

When making code changes in this repository, you MUST update the relevant documentation file(s) in the same edit batch. Do not defer doc updates to a separate step.

## Trigger Rules

| Files changed | Doc(s) to update |
|---------------|-----------------|
| `packages/db/prisma/schema.prisma` | `docs/DATA.md` — update the Schema section |
| `packages/agents/**` | `docs/AGENTS.md` — update or add the agent entry |
| New service added or data flow changed | `docs/ARCHITECTURE.md` — update diagram and service descriptions |
| New env var added to `packages/shared/src/env.ts` | `docs/DEPLOYMENT.md` — add to Environment Variables section; also add to `.env.example` |
| Render/Vercel/Docker config changed | `docs/DEPLOYMENT.md` — update relevant section |
| Any meaningful change | `CHANGELOG.md` — append a dated entry (most recent first) |

## Changelog Format

```markdown
## YYYY-MM-DD

### Brief title of change

- Bullet describing what was added/changed/removed
- Why it was done (optional, for non-obvious decisions)
```

## What counts as "meaningful"

- New feature, new route, new agent, new connector, new DB model
- Schema migration
- New environment variable
- Deployment config change
- Any architectural decision

Do NOT add a changelog entry for:
- Typo fixes
- Minor formatting changes
- Internal refactors with no external behavior change

## Doc Update Style

Keep updates minimal and accurate:
- Update only the affected section of a doc
- Don't rewrite entire docs
- Use the same format and heading structure already in the file
- For schema changes: update the table row(s) affected, not the entire schema section
- For agent changes: update the specific agent's entry only

## Sync Script

For mechanical regeneration (schema tables, type contracts), run:
```bash
pnpm sync:docs
```

This regenerates the auto-managed sections of `docs/DATA.md` and `docs/AGENTS.md` from source code.
